  "prompt": "Which is faster: Copying or Moving files in a PC? Why?",
  "response": "In general, copying files is faster than moving files on a PC. Here's why:\n\nCopying Files:\n- Creates a duplicate of the file in the destination\n- Original file remains untouched\n- Only requires writing new data to the destination\n- Faster process, especially for large files\n\nMoving Files:\n- Involves cutting the original file from source location\n- Requires both reading and writing data\n- Must update file system metadata\n- Involves removing file from original location\n- Slightly more complex and time-consuming process\n\nThe difference in speed is more noticeable:\n- When files are on the same physical drive: Moving is slower\n- When files are on different drives: Speed difference is minimal\n- With large files: Moving takes more time than copying\n\nFactors affecting speed:\n- Hard Drive type (SSD vs HDD)\n- File size\n- Drive performance\n- System resources\n\nPro Tip: For large file transfers, copying is generally recommended for faster and safer data transfer.",
